    <title>Supplement</title>
    <exercises>
        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <p>For <xref autoname="plural" ref="exercise-limits-supplement-first"/><ndash/><xref autoname="no" ref="exercise-limits-supplement-last"/>, state the limit suggested by the values in the table and state whether or not the limit exists.  The correct answer for <xref ref="exercise-limits-supplement-first"/> has been given to help you understand the instructions.</p> 
            </introduction>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-limits-supplement-first">
                <statement>
                    <tabular valign="top" top="major">
                        <col halign="right"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>t</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\fe{g}{t}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-10{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>99.97</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-100{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>999.997</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="major">
                            <cell><m>-1{,}000{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>9999.9997</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\text{Limit}&amp;&amp;&amp;\text{Limit Exists?}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{g}{t}&amp;=\infty&amp;&amp;\text{No}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>The relevant pattern in the <m>y</m> column is that <m>y</m> appears to be positive and growing by a little more than a factor of <m>10</m> every time <m>t</m> is negative and grows by a factor of <m>10</m>. It's not guaranteed, but this suggest that <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{g}{t}=\infty</m>. In this circumstance, we say that <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{g}{t}</m> does not exist.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{g}{t}=\infty</m>; <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{g}{t}</m> does not exist.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <tabular top="major" valign="top">
                        <col halign="right"/>
                        <col halign="right"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\fe{f}{x}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>51{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-3.2\times10^{-5}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>510{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-3.02\times10^{-7}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="major">
                            <cell><m>5{,}100{,}000</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-3.002\times10^{-9}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\text{Limit}&amp;&amp;&amp;\text{Limit Exists?}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to\mathord{?}}\mathord{?}&amp;=\mathord{?}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>The relevant pattern in the <m>y</m> column is the powers of <m>10</m>.  The first nonzero digit is moving farther and farther to the right of the decimal point. So the <m>y</m>-values are approaching zero. This suggest that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\fe{f}{x}=0</m>. So <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\fe{f}{x}</m> exists.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\fe{f}{x}=0</m>; <m>\lim\limits_{x\to0}\fe{f}{x}</m> exists.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <tabular top="major" valign="top">
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>t</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\fe{z}{t}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0.33</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>0.66</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0.333</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>0.666</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="major">
                            <cell><m>0.3333</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>0.6666</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\text{Limit}&amp;&amp;&amp;\text{Limit Exists?}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to\mathord{?}}\mathord{?}&amp;=\mathord{?}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>You should definitely recognize decimals approaching common fractions.  Good catch if you noted the <m>t</m> was approaching <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> only from the left. The suggested limit is <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\frac{1}{3}^{-}}\fe{z}{t}=\frac{2}{3}</m>, and this (one-sided) limit exists.</p> 
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lim\limits_{t\to\frac{1}{3}^{-}}\fe{z}{t}=\frac{2}{3}</m>; <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\frac{1}{3}^{-}}\fe{z}{t}</m> exists.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <tabular top="major" valign="top">
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>\theta</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\fe{g}{\theta}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-0.9</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2{,}999{,}990</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-0.99</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2{,}999{,}999</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="major">
                            <cell><m>-0.999</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2{,}999{,}999.9</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\text{Limit}&amp;&amp;&amp;\text{Limit Exists?}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to\mathord{?}}\mathord{?}&amp;=\mathord{?}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Stay focused when determining <q>from the left</q> or <q>from the right</q>; that can get tricky<ellipsis/>especially when the numbers are negative.  The limit suggested here is <m>\lim\limits_{\theta\to-1^{+}}\fe{g}{\theta}=3{,}000{,}000</m>. So this limit exists.</p> 
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lim\limits_{\theta\to-1^{+}}\fe{g}{\theta}=3{,}000{,}000</m>; <m>\lim\limits_{\theta\to-1^{+}}\fe{g}{\theta}</m> exists.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-limits-supplement-last">
                <statement>
                    <tabular top="major" valign="top">
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>t</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\fe{T}{t}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0.778</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>29{,}990</m></cell>
